        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nStatus post mitral valve repair, experiencing intermittent chest pain and shortness of breath.\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports being seen today for follow-up after her mitral valve repair on 8/3/2020. She states she's doing well overall, but has been experiencing intermittent chest pain and shortness of breath, particularly with exertion. She describes the chest pain as 'weird' and intermittent, lasting only a few minutes, and she's learning to slow down when she feels it. She's also noticed increased shortness of breath, describing it as 'shallow.' She's been taking her medications regularly and reports only mild irritability from the atenolol, which has lessened over time. She's taking coumadin 4mg daily, lasix 4mg daily, and atenolol 50mg daily.\nFindings\nPhysical exam reveals irregular irregular rhythm, trace peripheral edema on the extremities, and auscultation reveals reduced breath sounds bilaterally. The patient denies any fever, chills, or other acute symptoms. Examination of the head and neck reveals no jugular venous distension.\nAssessment\nThe patient's primary concern is intermittent chest pain and shortness of breath, likely related to atrial fibrillation and residual cardiac issues post-mitral valve repair. She remains stable on current medications.\nPlan",
